.]] || Was forbidden to serve by Federal authorities. ([[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] Loyalist)\n|-{{Party shading/Republican}}\n| [[Samuel Levy]], M.A. Walsh || 1872 || 1873 || [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] || Jointly appointed by Federal government, Levy was the first Jewish Mayor.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Samuel J. Ward]] || 1874 || 1874 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Sheriff of [[Caddo Parish]] in 1869. Born in Wales.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[W. Nick Murphy]] || 1875 || 1878 || [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]/[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Switched from Republican to Democrat.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Andrew Currie (Louisiana politician)|Andrew Currie]] || 1878 || 1889 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Resigned from his position in 1890.  Born in Ireland.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Edward B. Herndon]] || 1890 || 1890 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Elected to fill unfinished term. \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Richard Tucker Vinson]] || 1891 || 1895 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| Reuben Neil McKellar || 1896 || 1900 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Born in Kickapoo in [[Anderson County, Texas|Anderson County]], [[Texas]]; moved to Shreveport in his early teens\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Benjamin Holzman]] || 1900 || 1902 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Born in Germany.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Andrew Querbes|Andrew C. Querbes, Sr.]] || 1902 || 1906 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Born in [[New Orleans]].\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Ernest Ralph Berstein]] || 1906 || 1908 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Samuel Augustus Dickson]], M.D. || 1908 || 1910 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[John H. Eastman]] || 1910 || 1914 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || First mayor under [[city commission government]]\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Samuel Augustus Dickson]], M.D. || 1914 || 1916 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Robert Hodges Ward]] || 1916 || 1918 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Son of Mayor Samuel J. Ward.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[John McW. Ford|John McWilliams Ford]] || 1918 || 1922 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Lee Emmett Thomas]] || 1922 || 1930 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Louisiana State Representative, 1912\u20131916\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[J. G. Palmer]] || 1930 || 1932 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Louisiana State Judge.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[John McWilliams Ford]] || 1932 || 1932 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[George W. Hardy, Jr.]] || 1932 || 1934 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Louisiana State Judge.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Sam Caldwell|Samuel S. Caldwell]] || 1934 || 1946 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Clyde Fant|Clyde E. Fant]] || 1946 || 1954 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || \n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[James C. Gardner]] || 1954 || 1958 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Louisiana State Representative, 1952\u20131954\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Clyde Fant|Clyde E. Fant]] || 1958 || 1970 || [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] || Longest serving term of any Shreveport Mayor.\n|-{{Party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Calhoun Allen|L. Calhoun Allen, Jr.]] || 1970 || 1978 || [[Democratic Party