{"title_page": "Friedrich Wilhelm Rembert von Berg", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name=Friedrich Wilhelm Rembert von Berg\n|honorific_prefix= '''[[Graf]]'''\n|birth_date={{OldStyleDate|15 May|1794|26}}\n|death_date={{OldStyleDate|6 January|1874|18}} (aged 79)\n|birth_place= [[Sangaste#Sangaste castle|Sagnitz Manor]], [[Sangaste|Sagnitz]], [[Kreis Werro]], [[Governorate of Livonia|Riga Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]<br />(in present-day Sangaste, [[Valga County]], [[Estonia]])\n|death_place= [[St. Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire]]\n|resting_place= {{ill|Be\u013cava Manor, Pilskalns|lt=Kortenhof Manor|et|Be\u013cava m\u00f5is}}, [[Governorate of Livonia]] (in present-day {{ill|Pilskalns|lv|Pilskalns (Be\u013cavas pagasts)}}, [[Latvia]])\n|image= Fedor Fedorovich Berg 2.jpg\n|image_size=\n|caption= General Friedrich Wilhelm Rembert von Berg, c. 1860\n|monarch1=[[Nicholas I of Russia|Nicholas I]]<br>[[Alexander II of Russia|Alexander II]]\n|office1=[[Governor-General of Finland]]\n|predecessor1=[[Alexander Sergeyevich Menshikov|Alexander Menshikov]]\n|successor1=[[Platon Rokassovsky]]\n|term_start1={{OldStyleDate|19 December|1854|7}}\n|term_end1={{OldStyleDate|20 November|1861|8}}\n|office2=[[Namiestnik of Poland|Viceroy of the Kingdom of Poland]]\n|monarch2=[[Alexander II of Russia|Alexander II]]\n|term_start2={{OldStyleDate|31 October|1863|19}}\n|term_end2={{OldStyleDate|18 January|1874|6}}\n|predecessor2= [[Grand Duke Konstantin Nikolaevich of Russia|Grand Duke Konstantin Nikolaevich]]\n|successor2= Position abolished ([[Paul Demetrius von Kotzebue]] as the Governor-General of Warsaw)\n|nickname=\n|allegiance = {{flag|Russian Empire|1858}}\n|branch = {{army|Russian Empire|1858}}\n|serviceyears= 1812{{snd}}1874\n|rank=[[File:Imperial Russian Army 1904ic-p11r.png|30px|link=List of Russian Field Marshals]] [[List of Russian Field Marshals|General-Field Marshal]] \n|commands=\n|battles= {{hidden\n|''See battles''\n|{{tree list}}\n'''[[Napoleonic Wars]]'''\n** [[French invasion of Russia]]\n** [[War of the Sixth Coalition]]\n*** [[Battle of Leipzig]]\n{{hr}}\n'''[[Russo-Turkish War (1828-1829)]]'''\n** [[Battle of Adrianople (1829)|Battle of Adrianople]]\n{{hr}}\n'''[[November Uprising]]'''\n** [[Battle of Nur]]\n** [[Battle of Ostro\u0142\u0119ka (1831)|Battle of Ostro\u0142\u0119ka]]\n** [[Battle of Warsaw (1831)|Battle of Warsaw]]\n{{hr}}\n'''[[Crimean War]]'''\n** [[Crimean War#Baltic theatre|Baltic theatre]]\n{{hr}}\n'''[[January Uprising]]'''\n|-\n|headerstyle=background:#dbdbdb\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n|laterworks=\n|mawards=\n|signature=\u0411\u0435\u0440\u0433 \u0424. \u0424., \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444.jpg\n}}\n\n[[File:Berg-Wappen-Kattentack BWB.png|thumb|Coat of arms of the {{ill|Berg (Livonian noble family)|lt=Berg family|de|Berg (Livl\u00e4ndisches Adelsgeschlecht)}}, which belonged to the [[Uradel]], in the {{Interlanguage link multi|Baltic Coat of arms book|et|3=Baltisches Wappenbuch}} by {{Interlanguage link multi|Carl Arvid von Klingspor|de|3=Carl Arvid Klingspor}} in 1882.{{sfn|Klingspor|1882|p=10}}]]\n[[File:Graf Berg.jpg|thumb|Coat of arms of the counts of the family of 1856, in the Baltic Coat of arms book by Carl Arvid Klingspor in 1882.{{sfn|Klingspor|1882|p=10}}]]\n\n'''Friedrich Wilhelm Rembert Graf{{efn|{{German title Graf}}}} von Berg''' ({{lang-ru|\u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0433}}, [[Romanization of Russian|tr.]] {{transl|ru|F\u00ebdor F\u00ebdorovi\u010d Berg}}; {{OldStyleDate|15 May|1794|26}}{{snd}}{{OldStyleDate|6 January|1874|18}}) was a [[Baltic German]] nobleman, statesman, diplomat and general who served in the [[Imperial Russian Army]]. Berg was a [[Graf|count]] of the [[Austrian Empire]] and [[Grand Duchy of Finland]]<ref>[http://www.riddarhuset.fi/fi/index.php?id=13&sukunro=G011 Grevliga \u00e4tten nr 11 BERG] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022004800/http://www.riddarhuset.fi/fi/index.php?id=13&sukunro=G011 |date=2007-10-22 }} \u2013 [[Finnish House of Nobility]]</ref> and the 5th last man to be promoted [[List of Russian Field Marshals|General-Field Marshal]] in the history of the [[Russian Empire]]. He served as the [[Governor-General of Finland]]<ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Finland.html Governors-general of Finland]</ref> from 1854 to 1861 and the last [[Namiestnik of Poland|Viceroy of the Kingdom of Poland]] from 1863 to 1874.\n\nBerg was most notable for his role as the viceroy of Finland and Poland. He gained a reputation for his role in defending Finland and [[Governorate of Estonia|Estonia]] from [[Crimean War#Baltic theatre|Anglo-French invasion during the Crimean War]] and was also crucial in suppressing and crushing the [[Congress Poland|Polish]] [[January Uprising]] of 1863, during which rebel forces carried out numerous failed assassination attempts on him, martial law was consequently declared in Poland. Berg also held responsible for improving the economy and industry of Finland and Poland  during his time as viceroy. As a German, Berg was never keen of the [[Russification]] policies introduced in Poland, being opposed to the [[Pan-Slavism]] idealogy of the Russians and keen towards the foreign policies of [[German Confederation|Germany]]. He died in [[St. Petersburg]] in 1874 and was buried in his {{ill|Be\u013cava Manor, Pilskalns|lt=family estate|lv|Be\u013cavas mui\u017ea}} in the village of {{ill|Pilskalns|lt=Korten|lv|Pilskalns (Be\u013cavas pagasts)}}, [[Governorate of Livonia|Livonia]] (in now Pilskalns, [[Latvia]]).\n\n==Biography==\n===Origin===\n[[File:Sangaste m\u00f5isa peahoone2.jpg|thumb|The [[Sangaste Castle|Sagnitz castle]], where Count von Berg and his siblings spent their childhood in]]\n\nFriedrich Wilhelm Rembert von Berg was born on May 15, 1794 (26 according to the [[Julian calendar]] in use in [[Russian Empire|Russia]] at the time), in the [[Sangaste#Sangaste castle|family estate]] in the small village of [[Sangaste|Sagnitz]], [[Governorate of Livonia|Livonia]]. His father Friedrich Georg von Berg (1763-1811) was a state councillor and his mother Gertruda Wilhelmine [[Ermes (noble family)|von Ermes]] (1774-1844) was a young noblewoman, the younger Friedrich was the first cousin once removed{{efn|Gregor and Burchard Magnus von Berg were the children of Magnus Johann von Berg{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=660}}, while Magnus Johann was the brother{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=659}} of Gotthard Ernst who was the grandfather{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=661}} of Friedrich Wilhelm Rembert}} of generals Gregor (1765-1838) and Burchard Magnus von Berg (764-1838), both of who served in the [[Russian Imperial Army]] during the course of the [[Napoleonic Wars]]. Genealogists still debate{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=654-655}} where the {{ill|Berg (Livonian noble family)|lt=Livonian noble Berg family|de|Berg (Livl\u00e4ndisches Adelsgeschlecht}} originated in, many speculated they originated in [[Westphalia]]. The first known ancestor of the family to appear in [[Terra Mariana|Livonia]] was Otto von Berg. His son, who was also named Otto, was a vassal of the [[Livonian Knighthood]].\n\nFriedrich belonged to the Sagnitz branch of the Luist line of the family. The Luist line{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=659}} was formed by Captain Gustav von Berg (1656-1715), and the further divided Sagnitz branch{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=661}} was formed by Friedrich's grandfather Major Gotthard Ernst von Berg (1714-1766).\n\n===Early life===\nBerg along with his siblings spent their childhood in the Sagnitz castle and were home educated by the young [[Friedrich Georg Wilhelm Struve]].<ref>[https://www.obs.ee/cgi-bin/w3-msql/vaatleja/artikkel.html?id=84 Fr. G. W. Struve Dorpat period]</ref> After he finished his home education he studied in the {{ill|Tartu Gymnasium|it=Governorate Gymnasium|et|Tartu Kubermangug\u00fcmnaasium}} in [[Tartu|Dorpat]]. Originally not seeking a military career as a family tradition, Berg enrolled into the [[Philosophy]] faculty of [[University of Tartu|Imperial University of Dorpat]] in 1810.{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=662}} But after [[Napoleon]] [[French invasion of Russia|invaded of Russia]] in 1812, Berg dropped out from university and voluntarily entered the [[Russian Imperial Army]].\n\n{{quote|Here he got all the money, with a backpack on his back and boots on a stick, he reached [[Kaunas|Kovno]] barefooted, where the men of General [[Magnus Gustav von Essen|Essen]] stood.{{sfn|Military Encyclopaedia|1911-1915|pp=478}}}}\n\nHe entered the army as a [[Fahnenjunker]] and was enlisted into the [[6th Libau Infantry Regiment]] which was stationed at the north-western part of Russia to defend against Napoleon. Berg's bravery during the war of 1812 rewarded him the rank of [[lieutenant]] from [[Alexander I of Russia|Alexander I]] personally. He was also appointed second to the [[quartermaster]] due to his high education and being multilingual among Russian soldiers at the time.\n\nAfter Napoleon was pushed out of Russia, Berg was transferred to a [[Partisan (military)|partisan unit]] under the commands of [[Friedrich Karl von Tettenborn|Baron von Tettenborn]] and [[Pavel Kutuzov]] and took part in actions in [[Germany]] including the [[Battle of Leipzig]].\n\n===Family===\nBerg was born the eldest son of a family with three siblings, including his younger brother Gustav \"Astaf\" Gotthard Karl von Berg, the owner of the {{ill|Vecate Manor|It=Alt-Ottenhof Manor|et|Vecate m\u00f5is}}.{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=662}} His other brother [[Alexander von Berg|Alexander]] was a diplomat and [[Consul (representative)|consul]] in [[Naples]] and [[London]].{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=662}} Count von Berg married late in his life. In 1839, he married{{sfn|Stackelberg|1930|pp=662}} a rich [[Milan]]ese aristocrat Leopoldina {{ill|Cicogna-Mozzoni|it|Cicogna-Mozzoni}} (1786-1874), the widow of the Italian politician [[Alessandro Annoni]], with whom he had no children. However, after his brother Gustav's death in 1861, Friedrich adopted his orphaned nephews and brought them under his care:\n\n* Friedrich Georg Magnus Graf von Berg (1845-1938)\n* Alexander Rembert Joachim Graf von Berg (1847-1893)\n* Georg Erich Rembert Graf von Berg (1849-1920)\n* Emilie Wilhelmine \"Minni\" Anna Marie Ulrike Pauline Gr\u00e4fin von Berg (1852-1945)\n\nSince his marriage was childless, his [[Austrian Empire|Austrian]] and [[Grand Duchy of Finland|Finnish]] comital titles were inherited by his nephews/adoptive children.\n\n==Honours and awards==\n===Russian===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n*[[File:RUS Imperial Order of Saint Anna ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of St. Anna]] [[Order of St. Anna]], 3rd class (1813)\n*[[File:RUS Imperial Order of Saint Vladimir ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of St. Vladimir]] [[Order of St. Vladimir]], 4th class with a bow (1813)\n*[[File:RUS Imperial Order of Saint Anna ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of St. Anna]] Order of St. Anna, 1st class with the Imperial Crown (1828, Imperial Crown in 1831)\n*[[File:OrderStGeorge3cl rib.png|40px|link=Order of St. George]] [[Order of St. George]], 3rd class (25.6.181829)\n*[[File:RUS Imperial Order of Saint Vladimir ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of St. Vladimir]] Order of St. Vladimir, 2nd class (1829)\n*[[File:POL Virtuti Militari Komandorski BAR.svg|40px|link=Virtuti Militari]] [[Virtuti Militari|Order of Virtuti Militari]], ''Commander's Cross'' for military distinction (1831)\n*[[File:RUS Imperial Order of the White Eagle ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of the White Eagle (Russian Empire)]] [[Order of the White Eagle (Russian Empire)|Order of the White Eagle]] (1833)\n*[[File:RUS Imperial Order of Saint Alexander Nevsky ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of St. Alexander Nevsky]] [[Order of St. Alexander Nevsky]] (1838, diamonds signs in 1845)\n*[[File:RUS Imperial Order of Saint Vladimir ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of St. Vladimir]] Order of St. Vladimir, 1st class (1848)\n*[[File:Order of Glory Ribbon Bar.png|40px|link=Golden Sword of St. George]] [[Gold Sword for Bravery]] with diamonds and the inscription \"For a campaign to Hungary in 1849\" \n*[[File:RUS Imperial Order of Saint Andrew ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of St. Andrew]] [[Order of St. Andrew]] with swords and diamond signs (7.08.1855, diamond signs in 11.8.1861)\n\n===Foreign===\n*{{flag|Kingdom of Prussia}}:\n** [[File:D-PRU Pour le Merite 1 BAR.svg|40px|link=Pour le M\u00e9rite]] [[Pour le M\u00e9rite]] with the Golden Crown (1813, Golden Crown in 1864)\n** [[File: PRU Roter Adlerorden BAR.svg|40px|link=Order of the Red Eagle]] [[Order of the Red Eagle]], 1st class (1835)\n** [[File:Order of the Black Eagle - Ribbon bar.svg|40px|link=Order of the Black Eagle]] [[Order of the Black Eagle]] with diamond marks (1845, diamond marks in 1865)\n*{{flag|Kingdom of the Netherlands}}:\n** [[File:NLD Order of the Dutch Lion - Grand Cross BAR.png|40px|link=Order of the Netherlands Lion]] [[Order of the Netherlands Lion]], ''Great Cross'' (1849)\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Hungary}}:\n** [[File:Ord.S.Stef.Ungh. - GC.png|40px|link=Order of Saint Stephen of Hungary]] [[Order of Saint Stephen of Hungary|Order of St. Stephen of Hungary]], ''Nagykereszt'' (1849)\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Sweden}}:\n** [[File:Seraphimerorden ribbon.svg|40px|link=Order of the Seraphim]] [[Order of the Seraphim]] with diamond marks (1859, diamonds marks on 17.8.1860)\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Greece}}:\n** [[File:GRE Order Redeemer 1Class.png|40px|link=Order of the Redeemer]] [[Order of the Redeemer]], ''Great Cross'' (1868)\n}}\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''Le feldmar\u00e9chal-comte Berg, namiestnik dans le royaume de Pologne''. Notice biographique. [[Warsaw]] 1872 \u2013 [[Autobiography]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://personen.digitale-sammlungen.de/baltlex/Blatt_bsb00000600,00671.html?prozent=|title=Genealogische Handbuch der ba